ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u3011\u5927\u57d4\u3001\u6c99\u7530\u3001\u6cb9\u5858\u591a\u5340\u5c45\u6c11\u665a\u4e0a\u63a5\u529b\u5927\u5408\u5531|publisher=HK01|access-date=12 September 2019|lang=zh-hk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191118055847/https://www.hk01.com/18%E5%8D%80%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E/374281/%E7%A4%BE%E5%8D%80%E5%A4%A7%E5%90%88%E5%94%B1-%E5%A4%A7%E5%9F%94-%E6%B2%99%E7%94%B0-%E6%B2%B9%E5%A1%98%E5%A4%9A%E5%8D%80%E5%B1%85%E6%B0%91%E6%99%9A%E4%B8%8A%E6%8E%A5%E5%8A%9B%E5%A4%A7%E5%90%88%E5%94%B1|archive-date=18 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AutoK9-4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinesewords.org/dict/257792-40.html|publisher=Chinese Words|access-date=14 September 2019|script-title=zh:\u69ae\u5149\u8a5e\u8a9e\u89e3\u91cb / \u69ae\u5149\u662f\u4ec0\u9ebd\u610f\u601d|lang=zh-hk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190922115811/http://www.chinesewords.org/dict/257792-40.html|archive-date=22 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"originalvideo\">{{Cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y7yRDOLCy4Y|script-title=zh:\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u539f\u7248 \u300aGlory to Hong Kong\u300bFirst version (with ENG subs)|via=YouTube|access-date=16 September 2019|lang=zh-yue|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916020543/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y7yRDOLCy4Y|archive-date=16 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Glory to Hong Kong}}\n\n* {{YouTube|y7yRDOLCy4Y|Glory to Hong Kong}}\n* {{YouTube|jXZNOecZreY|Official English version}}\n* [https://sites.google.com/view/glorytohongkong/ Official website (Cantonese)]\n* [https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1pePpwJnh6p6hICjFD2A9c1H2SD-YazevzpplynMXXjc/ Resources released by composer (Cantonese)]\n* {{YouTube|oUIDL4SB60g|Orchestra and chorus edition}}\n\n{{2019 Hong Kong protests|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]]\n[[Category:2019 songs]]\n[[Category:Asian anthems]]\n[[Category:Chinese patriotic songs]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2019]]\n[[Category:Music memes]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong songs]]\n[[Category:Political party songs]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Song of the 2019 Hong Kong protests}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = \u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\"<br>\"Glory to Hong Kong\n| type          = song\n| artist        = \n| cover         = Glory to Hong Kong cover.jpg\n| cover_size    = \n| language      = Cantonese\n| written       = June\u2013August 2019\n| published     = 31 August 2019\n| released      = \n| format        = [[Streaming media]]\n| recorded      = 28\u201329 August 2019\n| genre         = \n*Fighting song\n*[[protest song]]\n*[[war song|military song]]\n*[[hymn]]<ref name=ThompsonTGaM/>\n| length        = {{Duration|m=1|s=45}}\n| composer      =  Thomas dgx yhl\n| lyricist      = \n*Thomas dgx yhl\n*public netizens on [[LIHKG]]\n}}\n{{Listen\n| filename    = \n| title       = \"Glory to Hong Kong\"\n| type        = music\n| description = Cantonese version (1:50)\n}}\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| video1 = {{YouTube|y7yRDOLCy4Y|\"Glory to Hong Kong\"}}\n| video2 = {{YouTube|jXZNOecZreY|\"Glory to Hong Kong\" official English version}}\n| video3 = {{YouTube|oUIDL4SB60g|\"Glory to Hong Kong\" orchestra and chorus edition}}}}\n{{Chinese\n|t=\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\n|p=Yu\u00e0n R\u00f3nggu\u0101ng Gu\u012b Xi\u0101ngg\u01ceng\n|bpmf=\u3129\u3122\u02cb \u3116\u3128\u3125\u02ca \u310d\u3128\u3124 \u310d\u3128\u311f \u3112\u3127\u3124 \u310d\u3124\u02c7\n|j=Jyun6 Wing4 Gwong1 Gwai1 Hoeng1 Gong2\n|y=Yuhn W\u00echng Gw\u014dng Gw\u0101i H\u0113ung G\u00f3ng\n|l=May Glory Return to Hong Kong\n|mi={{IPAc-cmn|yuan|4|.|r|ong|2|-|g|uang|1|.|g|ui|1|-|x|iang|1|.|g|ang|3|}}\n|ci = {{IPA-yue|jy:n\u02e8 w\u026a\u014b\u02e8\u02e9.kw\u0254:\u014b\u02e5 kw\u0250i\u02e5 h\u0153:\u014b\u02e5.k\u0254:\u014b\u02e7|}}}}\n\"'''Glory to Hong Kong'''\" is a [[Cantonese]] [[March (music)|march]] composed and written by a musician under the pseudonym \"Thomas dgx yhl\", with the contribution of a group of [[Hongkongers|Hongkonger]] [[netizen]]s from [[Internet forum|online forum]] [[LIHKG]] during the [[2019 Hong Kong protests]]. It has been widely adopted as the [[anthem]] of these protests, with some even regarding it as the \"[[national anthem]] of Hong Kong\".<ref name=\"time\"/><ref name=\"NYT\"/>\n\nSince widespread protests in Hong Kong erupted in early June 2019, various songs that symbolise democracy, such as \"[[Do You Hear the People Sing?|Do You Hear The People Sing]]\" from ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]'', have been sung by protesters on different occasions as their anthems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/arts-culture/article/3026843/hong-kong-protest-songs-7-anthems-anti-extradition-movement|title=Do you hear the people sing? 7 Hong Kong protest anthems|date=12 September 2019|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=29 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929062020/https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/arts-culture/article/3026843/hong-kong-protest-songs-7-anthems-anti-extradition-movement|archive-date=29 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Glory to Hong Kong\", according to the composer, was created \"to boost protesters' [[morale]] and unite people\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/video/scmp-originals/3030172/glory-hong-kong-composer-citys-protest-anthem-speaks|title=Who wrote Glory to Hong Kong?|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=29 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928171003/https://www.scmp.com/video/scmp-originals/3030172/glory-hong-kong-composer-citys-protest-anthem-speaks|archive-date=28 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>. Since the song's publication, it has been sung at most demonstrations. There are also numerous versions in English and other languages circulating the web.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-49661135|title=How Hong Kong got a new protest song|publisher=BBC|date=14 September 2019|access-date=29 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923223238/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-49661135|archive-date=23 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThomas, a music composer and Chinese lyricist, first posted an instrumental version of Glory to Hong Kong and its lyrics on 26 August 2019 to [[LIHKG]], an online forum where pro-democracy  [[Hongkongers]] exchange views. After receiving suggestions from the forum users, he amended the lyrics, including the incorporation of the phrase \"[[Liberate Hong Kong, the revolution of our times|Liberate Hong Kong; revolution of our times]]\" ({{zh|t=\u5149\u5fa9\u9999\u6e2f\uff0c\u6642\u4ee3\u9769\u547d|cy=Gw\u014dngfuhk h\u0113ungg\u00f3ng, s\u00echdoih gaakmihng}}), a motto at the protests. The song's music video, comprising scenes from demonstrations, was uploaded to YouTube on 31 August 2019.<ref name=\"originalvideo\"/> The song went viral within a few days across various social media, followed by the emergence of versions in English and [[Glory to Hong Kong#Other languages|other languages]].<ref name=\"time\"/><ref name=\"NYT\"/><ref name=\"scmp\"/> An orchestral music video with [[SATB]] chorus was uploaded to YouTube on 11 September 2019, pulling 1.5 million views within a week.<ref name=\"time\"/><ref name=\"AutoK9-1\"/> Hong Kong protesters previously sung \"[[Do You Hear the People Sing?]]\" and \"[[Sing Hallelujah to the Lord]]\" as protest anthems, before adopting \"Glory to Hong Kong\" as their main anthem.<ref name=NYT />\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine, the author-composer said: \"Music is a tool for unity, I really felt like we needed a song to unite us and boost our morale. The message to listeners is that despite the unhappiness and uncertainty of our time, Hong Kong people will not surrender.\"<ref name=time/> In an interview with ''[[Stand News]]'', the composer explained his motivation to compose a new protest song for Hong Kong in place of songs commonly sung during protests such as \"[[Boundless Oceans, Vast Skies]]\" and \"Glory Days\", two songs by Hong Kong band [[Beyond (band)|Beyond]], describing the songs as \"not unpleasant to listen to\", but that their rhythm was somewhat out of place with the atmosphere during protests. The composer said he was predominantly a [[pop rock]] artist, noting that a classical-style production like \"Glory to Hong Kong\" was a personal first. Inspired by \"[[God Save the Queen]]\", \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\", the [[national anthem of Russia]], the \"[[Battle Hymn of the Republic]]\" and \"[[Gloria (Vivaldi)|Gloria in Excelsis Deo]]\" by [[Antonio Vivaldi]], he spent two months composing the song's melody working backwards from the line \u201cMay people reign, proud and free\u201d.<!-- Can anyone add the exact Cantonese lines corresponding to the reported excerpt? --><ref name=\"interview\" /><ref name=\"Nikkei\">{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/Hong-Kong-protests/Glory-to-Hong-Kong-anthem-born-of-turmoil-turns-into-music-of-hope|title='Glory to Hong Kong': anthem born of turmoil turns into music of hope|last=Smith|first=Ken|date=12 October 2019|website=Nikkei Asian Review|url-status=live|access-date=2019-10-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012080443/https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/Hong-Kong-protests/Glory-to-Hong-Kong-anthem-born-of-turmoil-turns-into-music-of-hope|archive-date=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe song was observed by {{failed verification span|some musical experts|date=January 2020}} to have similar motives to [[Roman Tam]]'s \"[[Below the Lion Rock (song)|Below the Lion Rock]]\",<ref name=\"HarbourTimes\"/>{{Unreliable source?|date=January 2020}} a Cantopop song highly regarded among Hong Kongers in association with the sense of [[Lion Rock Spirit|the region's common spirit]].\n\n==Origin of the title==\nThe word \"glory\" ([[wiktionary:\u69ae\u5149|\u69ae\u5149]]) in the song title consists of the Chinese characters for honour ({{zh|t=[[wiktionary:\u69ae|\u69ae]]|j=wing4|labels=no}}) and brilliance ({{zh|t=[[wiktionary:\u5149|\u5149]]|j=gwong1|labels=no}}).<ref name=\"AutoK9-4\"/> The term has been used in poems by [[Li Bai]] and a prose by [[Lu Xun]], in addition to being a common term used by Christians. The composer noted that he was irreligious, and described the last sentence \"Glory be to Hong Kong\" (literally \"I wish glory return to Hong Kong\") ({{lang-zh|\u6211\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f|links=no}}) as his twofold wish: that Hong Kong can regain its glory in the future, and that Hongkongers are willing to dedicate their pride and triumphs to the city.<ref name=\"interview\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestandnews.com/politics/%E5%B0%88%E8%A8%AA-%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E4%B9%8B%E6%AD%8C-%E8%AA%95%E7%94%9F-%E9%A1%98%E6%A6%AE%E5%85%89%E6%AD%B8%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF-%E5%89%B5%E4%BD%9C%E4%BA%BA-%E9%9F%B3%E6%A8%82%E6%98%AF%E5%87%9D%E8%81%9A%E4%BA%BA%E5%BF%83%E6%9C%80%E5%BC%B7%E6%AD%A6%E5%99%A8/|script-title=zh:\u3010\u5c08\u8a2a\u3011\u300c\u9999\u6e2f\u4e4b\u6b4c\u300d\u8a95\u751f\uff1f\u3000\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u5275\u4f5c\u4eba\uff1a\u97f3\u6a02\u662f\u51dd\u805a\u4eba\u5fc3\u6700\u5f37\u6b66\u5668|last=\u4e9e\u88f9|date=11 September 2019|website=Stand News|language=Chinese|access-date=16 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912053347/https://www.thestandnews.com/politics/%E5%B0%88%E8%A8%AA-%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E4%B9%8B%E6%AD%8C-%E8%AA%95%E7%94%9F-%E9%A1%98%E6%A6%AE%E5%85%89%E6%AD%B8%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF-%E5%89%B5%E4%BD%9C%E4%BA%BA-%E9%9F%B3%E6%A8%82%E6%98%AF%E5%87%9D%E8%81%9A%E4%BA%BA%E5%BF%83%E6%9C%80%E5%BC%B7%E6%AD%A6%E5%99%A8/|archive-date=12 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhile this is largely an antiquated term in modern Chinese, it is still in common usage in modern Vietnamese ({{vie|v=Vinh quang|hn=\u69ae\u5149|labels=no}}), Japanese ({{Nihongo||\u6804\u5149|eik\u014d}}) and Korean ({{Korean|\uc601\uad11|\u69ae\u5149|yeonggwang|labels=no}}).<ref name=\"AutoK9-4\"/>\n\n==Lyrics==\n<!--Note that the lyrics are protected by copyrights and not to be published on Wikipedia without a proper licence. See [[Wikipedia:Copyright violations]]-->\n\"Glory to Hong Kong\" comprises four [[Stanza|stanzas]] of lyrics in Cantonese . The author states that he prioritised the meaning of the lyrics over the rhyming of lines,<ref name=\"interview\" /> and explains the meaning of each stanza as follows:\n\nThe first [[:wikt: stanza|stanza]] solemnly describes the suppression and deprivation of fundamental [[human rights]], such as [[democracy]], [[liberty]] and [[justice]].<ref name=\"interview\" />\n\nThe second stanza describes the [[2019 Hong Kong protests|anti-ELAB movement]], where the people stand up to injustice even though blood is shed. The solemness follows that in the first stanza.<ref name=\"interview\" />\n\nThe third stanza describes the perseverance of Hong Kong people in darkness and despair. It is performed with slightly less solemn character.<ref name=\"interview\" />\n\nThe final stanza, with the most recognisable [[motto]] \"Liberate Hong Kong; revolution of our times\" incorporated in the [[lyrics]], envisages that the city will regain its glory and honour. It expresses hope for the future, ending the song with excitement.<ref name=\"interview\" />\n\n===Other languages===\nVarious versions of English lyrics have appeared online, with the most notable version from \"Seven Swords Spring and Autumn\" (literal translation from Chinese: \u4e03\u528d\u6d63\u6625\u79cb) on [[LIHKG]] on 7 September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lihkg.com/thread/1547782/page/1|script-title=zh:\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u82f1\u6587\u6b4c\u8a5e \"Glory be to Thee, Hong Kong\"|date=7 September 2019|website=LIHKG \u9023\u767b|publisher=\u4e03\u528d\u6d63\u6625\u79cb|language=zh-trad|trans-title=\"Glory to Hong Kong\" English lyrics \"Glory be to Thee, Hong Kong\"|url-status=live|access-date=1 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001023725/https://lihkg.com/thread/1547782/page/1|archive-date=1 October 2019|title=LIHKG}}</ref> Shek Ga-mak, a Hong Kong [[expatriate]] in Germany, released German lyrics for the song on 11 September 2019.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u3010\u5fb7\u6587\u7ffb\u8b6f\u3011\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u521d\u7a3f|url=https://www.thestandnews.com/politics/%E5%BE%B7%E6%96%87%E7%BF%BB%E8%AD%AF-%E9%A1%98%E6%A6%AE%E5%85%89%E6%AD%B8%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF-%E5%88%9D%E7%A8%BF/|access-date=24 September 2019|publisher=Stand News|date=11 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002075631/https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E5%BE%B7%E6%96%87%E7%BF%BB%E8%AD%AF-%E9%A1%98%E6%A6%AE%E5%85%89%E6%AD%B8%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF-%E5%88%9D%E7%A8%BF/|archive-date=2 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Japanese lyrics for the song were also released by an [[Anonymity|anonymous]] Japanese person on 18 September 2019.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u6211\u662f\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u65e5\u8a9e\u7248\u4f5c\u8005\uff0c\u9019\u662f\u6211\u7684\u4e00\u4e9b\u60f3\u6cd5|url=https://thestandnews.com/culture/%E6%88%91%E6%98%AF-%E9%A1%98%E6%A6%AE%E5%85%89%E6%AD%B8%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF-%E6%97%A5%E8%AA%9E%E7%89%88%E4%BD%9C%E8%80%85-%E9%80%99%E6%98%AF%E6%88%91%E7%9A%84%E4%B8%80%E4%BA%9B%E6%83%B3%E6%B3%95/|access-date=24 September 2019|publisher=Stand News|date=18 September 2019}}</ref> Members of Action Free Hong Kong Montreal performed a French version written by [[netizen]] assuming [[pseudonym]] \"Montreal Guy\", which was uploaded to [[YouTube]] on 26 September 2019.<ref>{{Citation|title=Que la gloire soit \u00e0 Hong Kong |script-title=zh:\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\uff1a\u6cd5\u6587\u7248\uff09\u5408\u5531\u6b4c\u8a5e\u7248 Lyric MV|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cGfjaBjP7Os|access-date=2019-10-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928161050/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cGfjaBjP7Os|archive-date=28 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkcnews.com/article/23810/\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f-\u6cd5\u6587-\u9003\u72af\u689d\u4f8b-23810/\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u6cd5\u6587\u7248\u5275\u4f5c\u7de3\u8d77|script-title=zh:\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u6cd5\u6587\u7248\u5275\u4f5c\u7de3\u8d77|website=\u773e\u65b0\u805e|language=zh|access-date=1 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001003044/https://www.hkcnews.com/article/23810/%25E9%25A1%2598%25E6%25A6%25AE%25E5%2585%2589%25E6%25AD%25B8%25E9%25A6%2599%25E6%25B8%25AF-%25E6%25B3%2595%25E6%2596%2587-%25E9%2580%2583%25E7%258A%25AF%25E6%25A2%259D%25E4%25BE%258B-23810/%25E3%2580%258A%25E9%25A1%2598%25E6%25A6%25AE%25E5%2585%2589%25E6%25AD%25B8%25E9%25A6%2599%25E6%25B8%25AF%25E3%2580%258B%25E6%25B3%2595%25E6%2596%2587%25E7%2589%2588%25E5%2589%25B5%25E4%25BD%259C%25E7%25B7%25A3%25E8%25B5%25B7|archive-date=1 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>. ''P\u00edcnic per la Rep\u00fablica'' released and sung a [[Catalan language|Catalan]] version on 24 October 2019 in front of the Chinese Consulate of Barcelona.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Cantan-Barcelona-Hong-Kong-democracia_0_956105072.html|title=Cantan en Barcelona el himno de protestas de Hong Kong para pedir democracia|date=24 October 2019|url-status=live|access-date=26 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026003538/https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Cantan-Barcelona-Hong-Kong-democracia_0_956105072.html|archive-date=26 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PicnicxRep/status/1187351775503966208|title=Glory to Hong Kong. Today, in Barcelona!|date=24 October 2019|url-status=live|access-date=26 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191024125746/https://twitter.com/PicnicxRep/status/1187351775503966208|archive-date=24 October 2019}}</ref> A Taiwanese version was premiered by the indie band ''The Chairman'' during a solidarity concert in Taipei on 17 November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/acn/201911200105.aspx|script-title=zh:\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u53f0\u8a9e\u7248MV \u842c\u4eba\u633a\u6e2f\u58ef\u89c0\u9707\u64bc[\u5f71] &#124; \u5169\u5cb8 &#124; \u4e2d\u592e\u793e CNA|website=www.cna.com.tw|access-date=21 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120124510/https://www.cna.com.tw/news/acn/201911200105.aspx|archive-date=20 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Public use==\n[[File:Glory to Hong Kong in Time Square 20190912.jpg|220px|thumb|People singing the song at [[Times Square (Hong Kong)|Times Square]], Causeway Bay<ref name=\"stand911\" />]]\n[[File:Hong Kong Stadium people sang Glory to Hong Kong 20190910.jpg|220px|thumb|Football fans singing the song during Hong Kong's match against Iran on 10 September]]\n[[File:Glory to Hong Kong in New Town Plaza 20190911.jpg|220px|thumb|Around 1000 people singing the song \"Glory to Hong Kong\" in [[New Town Plaza]]<ref name=\"stand911\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestandnews.com/politics/%E7%9D%87%E7%89%87-%E9%A1%98%E6%A6%AE%E5%85%89%E6%AD%B8%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF-%E5%86%8D%E9%9F%BF%E9%81%8D%E5%A4%9A%E5%8D%80%E5%95%86%E5%A0%B4-%E5%8D%83%E4%BA%BA%E8%BF%AB%E7%88%86%E6%96%B0%E5%9F%8E%E5%B8%82%E5%BB%A3%E5%A0%B4/|script-title=zh:\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u518d\u97ff\u904d\u591a\u5340\u5546\u5834\u3000\u5343\u4eba\u8feb\u7206\u65b0\u57ce\u5e02\u5ee3\u5834|date=11 September 2019|website=Stand News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914044519/https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E7%9D%87%E7%89%87-%E9%A1%98%E6%A6%AE%E5%85%89%E6%AD%B8%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF-%E5%86%8D%E9%9F%BF%E9%81%8D%E5%A4%9A%E5%8D%80%E5%95%86%E5%A0%B4-%E5%8D%83%E4%BA%BA%E8%BF%AB%E7%88%86%E6%96%B0%E5%9F%8E%E5%B8%82%E5%BB%A3%E5%A0%B4/|archive-date=14 September 2019|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref>]]\nThe song has been sung on numerous occasions by citizens in the public all over the city.<ref name=\"scmp3027265\" /> 200 people participated in a [[sit-in]] at [[Prince Edward station]] on 6 September 2019, requesting [[MTR]] to hand over footage of the [[List_of_August_2019_Hong_Kong_protests#31_August_protest|attacks on passengers conducted by police on 31 August]]; in addition to chanting slogans, the protesters sang this anthem and \"Do You Hear the People Sing?\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestandnews.com/politics/%E5%B0%91%E5%A5%B3%E5%A4%AA%E5%AD%90%E7%AB%99%E8%B7%AA%E6%B1%82%E6%B8%AF%E9%90%B5%E5%85%AC%E9%96%8B-8-31-cctv-%E6%B8%AF%E9%90%B5-%E7%89%87%E6%AE%B5%E6%9C%83%E4%BF%9D%E7%95%99-3-%E5%B9%B4/|language=zh-yue|script-title=zh:\u5c11\u5973\u592a\u5b50\u7ad9\u8dea\u6c42\u516c\u958b 8.31 CCTV\u3000\u903e\u767e\u5e02\u6c11\u52a0\u5165\u3000\u6e2f\u9435\uff1a\u7247\u6bb5\u6703\u4fdd\u7559 3 \u5e74|publisher=Stand News|date=6 September 2019|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910193523/https://www.thestandnews.com/politics/%E5%B0%91%E5%A5%B3%E5%A4%AA%E5%AD%90%E7%AB%99%E8%B7%AA%E6%B1%82%E6%B8%AF%E9%90%B5%E5%85%AC%E9%96%8B-8-31-cctv-%E6%B8%AF%E9%90%B5-%E7%89%87%E6%AE%B5%E6%9C%83%E4%BF%9D%E7%95%99-3-%E5%B9%B4/|archive-date=10 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A few hundred people sang the song together at [[Cityplaza]] on 9 September.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/world/breakingnews/2910902|language=zh-hant|script-title=zh:\u53cd\u9001\u4e2d\u300b\u9707\u64bc\uff01\u6578\u767e\u6e2f\u4eba\u65bc\u592a\u53e4\u57ce\u4e2d\u5fc3\u9ad8\u5531\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b|publisher=Liberty Times Net|date=9 September 2019|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004152759/https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/world/breakingnews/2910902|archive-date=4 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 September, [[Hong Kong national football team|Hong Kong]] football supporters sang the song at a match for the first time during a [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|FIFA World Cup qualification]] match against [[Iran national football team|Iran]], booing the Chinese anthem.<ref name=\"aljazeera\" /> On the same night, the song was again publicly sung by large groups at more than a dozen shopping malls across Hong Kong at 8:31&nbsp;pm, a reference to both the police attacks on 31 August and the [[2014 NPCSC Decision on Hong Kong]] which was declared on 31 August 2014.<ref name=\"AutoK9-3\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rfi.fr/tw/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9C%8B/20190911-%E6%8A%97%E7%88%AD%E6%AD%8C%E9%A1%98%E6%A6%AE%E5%85%89%E6%AD%B8%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF8%E6%99%8231%E5%88%86%E9%9F%BF%E9%81%8D%E5%85%A8%E6%B8%AF%E5%8B%BF%E5%BF%98%E5%8F%97%E5%82%B7%E7%A4%BA%E5%A8%81%E8%80%85|language=zh-hant|script-title=zh:\u6297\u722d\u6b4c\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b8\u664231\u5206\u97ff\u904d\u5168\u6e2f\u52ff\u5fd8\u53d7\u50b7\u793a\u5a01\u8005|publisher=[[Radio France Internationale]]|date=11 September 2019|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911234248/http://www.rfi.fr/tw/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9C%8B/20190911-%E6%8A%97%E7%88%AD%E6%AD%8C%E9%A1%98%E6%A6%AE%E5%85%89%E6%AD%B8%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF8%E6%99%8231%E5%88%86%E9%9F%BF%E9%81%8D%E5%85%A8%E6%B8%AF%E5%8B%BF%E5%BF%98%E5%8F%97%E5%82%B7%E7%A4%BA%E5%A8%81%E8%80%85|archive-date=11 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 11 September, around 100 people sang the song together in a memorial meeting for a suicide victim held at [[Ka Shing Court]] in [[Fanling]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestandnews.com/society/%E7%B2%89%E5%B6%BA%E5%A5%B3%E5%AD%90%E4%B8%8A%E5%91%A8%E5%A2%AE%E6%A8%93%E4%BA%A1-%E7%99%BE%E5%90%8D%E8%A1%97%E5%9D%8A%E8%BF%BD%E6%80%9D%E6%82%BC%E5%BF%B5/|language=zh-yue|script-title=zh:\u7c89\u5dba\u5973\u5b50\u4e0a\u5468\u58ae\u6a13\u4ea1\u3000\u767e\u540d\u8857\u574a\u8ffd\u601d\u60bc\u5ff5|publisher=Stand News|date=11 September 2019|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191118055921/https://www.thestandnews.com/society/%E7%B2%89%E5%B6%BA%E5%A5%B3%E5%AD%90%E4%B8%8A%E5%91%A8%E5%A2%AE%E6%A8%93%E4%BA%A1-%E7%99%BE%E5%90%8D%E8%A1%97%E5%9D%8A%E8%BF%BD%E6%80%9D%E6%82%BC%E5%BF%B5/|archive-date=18 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Around 500 students from 10 secondary schools in [[Kwun Tong District]], [[Tseung Kwan O]] and [[Kowloon City District]] organized a [[Human chain (politics)|human chain]], in which they sang the song.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mingpao.com/ins/%E6%B8%AF%E8%81%9E/article/20190911/s00001/1568195092144/%E3%80%90%E9%80%83%E7%8A%AF%E6%A2%9D%E4%BE%8B-%E5%A4%9A%E5%9C%96%E3%80%91%E8%81%AF%E6%A0%A1%E4%B8%AD%E5%AD%B8%E7%94%9F%E4%B9%9D%E9%BE%8D%E5%A1%98%E7%AF%89%E4%BA%BA%E9%8F%88%E7%88%AD%E5%8F%96%E4%BA%94%E5%A4%A7%E8%A8%B4%E6%B1%82|language=zh-hant|script-title=zh:\u3010\u9003\u72af\u689d\u4f8b\uff0e\u591a\u5716\u3011\u806f\u6821\u4e2d\u5b78\u751f\u4e5d\u9f8d\u5858\u7bc9\u4eba\u93c8\u722d\u53d6\u4e94\u5927\u8a34\u6c42|work=[[Ming Pao]]|date=11 September 2019|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911191010/https://news.mingpao.com/ins/%e6%b8%af%e8%81%9e/article/20190911/s00001/1568195092144/%e3%80%90%e9%80%83%e7%8a%af%e6%a2%9d%e4%be%8b-%e5%a4%9a%e5%9c%96%e3%80%91%e8%81%af%e6%a0%a1%e4%b8%ad%e5%ad%b8%e7%94%9f%e4%b9%9d%e9%be%8d%e5%a1%98%e7%af%89%e4%ba%ba%e9%8f%88%e7%88%ad%e5%8f%96%e4%ba%94%e5%a4%a7%e8%a8%b4%e6%b1%82|archive-date=11 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Around 1000 people sang the song in [[New Town Plaza]] together that night, with crowds of people singing the song in other shopping malls around Hong Kong as well.<ref name=\"stand911\"/>\n\n==Reception==\nRobyn Dixon and Marcus Yam of ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' described \"Glory to Hong Kong\" as having \"a more indigenous, electric, unifying effect\" when compared to previously used songs at protests.<ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2019-09-13/glory-to-hong-kong-a-new-protest-anthem-moves-singers-to-tears|title='Glory to Hong Kong': A new protest anthem moves singers to tears|last1=Dixon|first1=Robyn|date=13 September 2019|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=16 September 2019|last2=Yam|first2=Marcus|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916124036/https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2019-09-13/glory-to-hong-kong-a-new-protest-anthem-moves-singers-to-tears|archive-date=16 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The march's [[Cantonese]] lyrics, in particular, affirms a sense of a collective cultural identity which is at the heart of the conflict<ref name=ThompsonTGaM>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-whats-in-a-song-for-the-people-of-hong-kong-the-idea-of-nationhood/|title=Opinion: What's in a song? For the people of Hong Kong, the idea of nationhood|last=Thompson|first=Brian C.|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=20 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920004636/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-whats-in-a-song-for-the-people-of-hong-kong-the-idea-of-nationhood/|archive-date=20 September 2019|url-status=live|quote=Culture and identity are also at the heart of the conflict, and it\u2019s revealed through the languages of these two anthems. The people of Hong Kong are deeply attached to Cantonese language and to the use of classical Chinese characters. They have seen the Central Government funnel Mandarin-speaking immigrants into Hong Kong, and designer stores cater to Mainland visitors with signage written in simplified characters. Singing Glory to Hong Kong in Cantonese affirms a sense of identity that demands fighting for.}}</ref> The lyrics evokes a sense of pride and belonging to Hong Kongers who struggle for identity after the 1997 hand-over to China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chow |first1=Vivienne |title=I've Been Waiting for a Song Like 'Glory to Hong Kong' My Whole Life |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/16/opinion/hong-kong-anthem.html |accessdate=27 December 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=16 September 2019}}</ref> The [[hymn]]-like composition was also seen as \"supremely approachable\" to the populace who were accustomed to the Christian music tradition introduced by the region's [[Education in Hong Kong#History|British and missionary-influenced educational system]].<ref name=\"Nikkei\" />\n\nThe Chinese edition of ''[[Deutsche Welle]]'' named \"Glory to Hong Kong\" the \"anthem\" of the Hong Kong protests.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/zh/%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E6%8A%97%E8%AD%B0%E9%81%8B%E5%8B%95%E7%9A%84%E4%B8%BB%E9%A1%8C%E6%9B%B2/av-50399940|language=zh-hans|script-title=zh:\u9999\u6e2f\u6297\u8bae\u8fd0\u52a8\u7684\"\u4e3b\u9898\u66f2\"|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|date=1 September 2019|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913165425/https://www.dw.com/zh/%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E6%8A%97%E8%AD%B0%E9%81%8B%E5%8B%95%E7%9A%84%E4%B8%BB%E9%A1%8C%E6%9B%B2/av-50399940|archive-date=13 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Chinese edition of [[Voice of America]] describes the lyrics of the song as reflecting the heartfelt views of protestors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.voachinese.com/a/Hong-Kong-Protests-Anthem-Glory-To-HK-20190913/5082166.html|language=zh-hans|script-title=zh:\u300a\u613f\u8363\u5149\u5f52\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u8bcd\u66f2\u9053\u51fa\u793a\u5a01\u8005\u5fc3\u58f0|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|date=1 September 2019|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913213301/https://www.voachinese.com/a/Hong-Kong-Protests-Anthem-Glory-To-HK-20190913/5082166.html|archive-date=13 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Taiwanese newspaper ''[[Liberty Times]]'' described the song as \"the military march of protesters\" ({{zh|\u6297\u722d\u8005\u8ecd\u6b4c}}), singing their anxiety towards Hong Kong's political situation, as well as an \"unrelenting revolutionary spirit\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/world/breakingnews/2902135|language=zh-hant|script-title=zh:\u53cd\u9001\u4e2d\u300b\u6e2f\u4eba\u539f\u5275\u6297\u722d\u8005\u8ecd\u6b4c \u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300bMV\u66dd\u5149|work=Liberty Times|date=31 August 2019|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905164133/https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/world/breakingnews/2902135|archive-date=5 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Describing the song, [[Chinese Television System]] News noted that the song had \"peaceful vocals coupled with scenes of bloody conflicts between Hong Kong Police and the people\" and that by creating \"Glory to Hong Kong\", Hongkongers recorded their \"history of struggling for democracy and freedom\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.cts.com.tw/cts/international/201909/201909061973809.html|language=zh-hant|script-title=zh:\u6e2f\u4eba\u81ea\u5275\"\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\" MV\u64bc\u4eba\u5fc3|publisher=Chinese Television System|date=6 September 2019|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923183253/https://news.cts.com.tw/cts/international/201909/201909061973809.html|archive-date=23 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[:zh:\u5468\u4fdd\u677e|Chow Po-chung]], a professor of politics and public administration at the [[Chinese University of Hong Kong]] noted that the song's melody and lyrics resonated with many people and united protesters, leading to many people developing great \"attachment\" to the song.<ref name=\"BBCZ\">{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u9999\u6e2f\u300c\u53cd\u9001\u4e2d\u300d\u6b4c\u66f2\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u88ab\u5c01\u300c\u570b\u6b4c\u300d\u5f15\u767c\u722d\u8b70|url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/trad/chinese-news-49673333|access-date=14 September 2019|publisher=BBC Chinese|date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008033650/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/trad/chinese-news-49673333|archive-date=8 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>Former [[President of the Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] [[Jasper Tsang]] praised the song a high-quality technical production and believing it to be produced by professional musicians. He said that the song shows that the government's efforts at promotion have been weak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1480517-20190914.htm|title=Tsang Yok-sing pins unrest on social inequality|date=14 September 2019|website=RTHK|access-date=24 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916035226/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1480517-20190914.htm|archive-date=16 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''[[Wen Wei Po]]'', a state-owned newspaper controlled by the [[Hong Kong Liaison Office]], published an article on its front page on 12 September, criticising the song as the anthem for [[Hong Kong independence]], and that the lyrics idealize violence. The title of the article \u7368\u6b4c\u6d17\u8166\uff0c\u717d\u8d70\u7368\u8def may be translated as \"independence song brainwashes, touting independence as the route [for Hong Kong]\", though \"independence\" may be treated as a pun for \"poison\" in this context due to its Chinese pronunciation.<ref name=\"BBCZ\"/> [[:zh:\u6f58\u9e97\u74ca|Carmen Poon]] published an article in ''[[Ming Pao]]'' on 13 September entitled \"the brainwashing song that trumpets Hong Kong independence\" ({{zh|\u9f13\u5439\u6e2f\u7368\u7684\u6d17\u8166\u6b4c}}), in which she describes the \"elegant lyrics\" of the song as \"advocating hate\", and that \"seeds of violence and hatred have been sown into the brainwashing song, causing people to inadvertently dance to its [[Baton (conducting)|baton]] and commit bad behaviour\".<ref>{{cite news|last=\u6f58|first=\u9e97\u74ca|script-title=zh:\u9f13\u5439\u6e2f\u7368\u7684\u6d17\u8166\u6b4c|url=https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%E4%BD%9C%E5%AE%B6%E5%B0%88%E6%AC%84/article/20190913/s00018/1568313663739/%E9%BC%93%E5%90%B9%E6%B8%AF%E7%8D%A8%E7%9A%84%E6%B4%97%E8%85%A6%E6%AD%8C|access-date=17 September 2019|work=Ming Pao|date=13 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913222842/https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%e4%bd%9c%e5%ae%b6%e5%b0%88%e6%ac%84/article/20190913/s00018/1568313663739/%e9%bc%93%e5%90%b9%e6%b8%af%e7%8d%a8%e7%9a%84%e6%b4%97%e8%85%a6%e6%ad%8c|archive-date=13 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u653fWhats\u564f\uff1a\u793a\u5a01\u8005\u4f5c\u57cb\u300c\u570b\u6b4c\u300d\uff1f\u3000\u5b78\u8005\uff1a\u60f3\u641e\u7368\u7acb|url=https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/news/20190912/bkn-20190912172803976-0912_00822_001.html|access-date=18 September 2019|agency=Oriental Daily News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923184737/https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/news/20190912/bkn-20190912172803976-0912_00822_001.html|archive-date=23 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe song has been described as the unofficial anthem of Hong Kong, and some protesters stated they felt that \"Glory to Hong Kong\" should replace the Chinese national anthem \"[[March of the Volunteers]]\" as the national anthem of Hong Kong;<ref name=\"AutoK9-2\" /><ref name=\"NYT\" /> to which, the composer insisted that the song can only be a [[protest song]]: \"There is no nation. How can there be a national anthem?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1707883/glory-to-hong-kong-is-citys-new-unofficial-anthem/|title=Singing showdowns in Hong Kong pit the city's unofficial new anthem against China's|author=Vivienne Chow|date=12 September 2019|work=Quartz|access-date=15 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913230100/https://qz.com/1707883/glory-to-hong-kong-is-citys-new-unofficial-anthem/|archive-date=13 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On the other hand, an opinion piece by Brian C. Thompson, a Chinese University of Hong Kong senior lecturer, for ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' argues that despite only a \"few\" minority of the protesters are [[separatism|demanding for a separate state]], the march is used as a thematic anthem representing the collective demands of the Hong Kong people \u2013 which are also considered \"a nation [...]. A state may be home to multiple nations...\" \u2013 therefore the march can still be regarded as \"national\" in nature.<ref name=ThompsonTGaM/>\n\nThere were also slight criticism with how the march was made in terms of {{failed verification span|musical theory|date=January 2020}} - its lyrics were seen in a professional sense as \"clumsy\" and its melodic range not only \"too wide for most amateur singers\" to which its lyrics' [[Cantonese#Tones|spoken tones]] are not synched by.<ref name=\"Nikkei\" /><ref name=\"HarbourTimes\">{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Jasmine |title=Glory to Hong Kong's bilingual significance, musicality, and more |url=https://harbourtimes.com/2019/09/20/glory-to-hong-kongs-bilingual-significance-musicality-and-more/ |accessdate=27 October 2019 |work=Harbour Times |date=September 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191027033248/https://harbourtimes.com/2019/09/20/glory-to-hong-kongs-bilingual-significance-musicality-and-more/ |archive-date=27 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe song has gained a huge popularity in Ukraine, as for the result of the song's name and slogan was inspired by the traditional Ukrainian slogan \"\u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0456! \u0413\u0435\u0440\u043e\u044f\u043c \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430!\" (''[[Glory to Ukraine]]! Glory to the heroes!'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.unn.com.ua/ru/news/1827596-slava-gonkongu-geroyam-slava-aktivisti-pereynyali-revolyutsiyni-gasla-ukrayini | title=\"\u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0413\u043e\u043d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0433\u0443! \u0413\u0435\u0440\u043e\u044f\u043c \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430!\": \u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u044f\u043b\u0438 \u0440\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044e\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043b\u043e\u0437\u0443\u043d\u0433\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b}}</ref> The Hong Kong's slogan version was also used by Ukrainian protesters in solidarity with the Hong Kong protesters.<ref>https://www.kyivpost.com/multimedia/video/ukrainians-support-hong-kong-activists-outside-the-chinese-embassy</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n[[:zh:\u674e\u5a49\u83ef|Anita Lee]], a host of [[Vancouver]]-based Chinese-language radio station [[CJVB]], received complaints from local Chinese residents after playing \"Glory to Hong Kong\" live on radio. She rejected rumours that she was suspended, whilst refusing to comment further.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u50b3\u674e\u5a49\u83ef\u52a0\u62ff\u5927\u96fb\u53f0\u7bc0\u76ee\u64ad\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u5f8c\u88ab\u5c01\u54aa |url=https://ol.mingpao.com/ldy/showbiz/latest/20190912/1568274543098/%E5%82%B3%E6%9D%8E%E5%A9%89%E8%8F%AF%E5%8A%A0%E6%8B%BF%E5%A4%A7%E9%9B%BB%E5%8F%B0%E7%AF%80%E7%9B%AE%E6%92%AD%E3%80%8A%E9%A1%98%E6%A6%AE%E5%85%89%E6%AD%B8%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E3%80%8B%E5%BE%8C%E8%A2%AB%E5%B0%81%E5%92%AA |accessdate=12 September 2019 |work=Ming Pao |date=12 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924015154/https://ol.mingpao.com/ldy/showbiz/latest/20190912/1568274543098/%e5%82%b3%e6%9d%8e%e5%a9%89%e8%8f%af%e5%8a%a0%e6%8b%bf%e5%a4%a7%e9%9b%bb%e5%8f%b0%e7%af%80%e7%9b%ae%e6%92%ad%e3%80%8a%e9%a1%98%e6%a6%ae%e5%85%89%e6%ad%b8%e9%a6%99%e6%b8%af%e3%80%8b%e5%be%8c%e8%a2%ab%e5%b0%81%e5%92%aa |archive-date=24 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[Apple Daily]]'' published an article on 15 September, quoting [[RTHK]] staff who claimed to have received a notice from their managers on 12 September which told them not to play the song outside of news and [[phone-in]] programmes for the needs of \"news broadcasting\" due to its ties with Hong Kong independence. The article also quoted that the song should be deleted from recordings of shows where previously played, due to an alleged violation of the RTHK Charter which states that RTHK should fulfil the purpose of \"engendering a sense of citizenship and national identity through programmes that contribute to the understanding of [Hong Kong's] community and nation\". After holding meetings with employees, Director of Broadcasting [[:zh:\u6881\u5bb6\u69ae (\u50b3\u5a92\u5de5\u4f5c\u8005)|Leung Ka-wing]] instead said that the song was to be avoided due to its controversial nature. Responding to the newspaper's enquiry, Ng Man-yee of RTHK responded that its management has not banned \"Glory to Hong Kong\", has not deleted the song from its database, and as far as she knows, has not discouraged playing the song.<ref>{{cite news |author1=\u6f58\u67cf\u6797 |script-title=zh:\u6e2f\u53f0\u7bc0\u76ee\u7981\u64ad\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b \u54e1\u5de5\u6536\u9ad8\u5c64\u901a\u77e5\u6307\u6b4c\u66f2\u6d89\u300c\u6e2f\u7368\u300d |url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/realtime/article/20190915/60045476 |accessdate=15 September 2019 |work=Apple Daily |date=15 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924020822/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/realtime/article/20190915/60045476 |archive-date=24 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLai Rifu, a [[Weiquan]] dissident, was arrested by [[Guangzhou]] police for [[picking quarrels and provoking trouble]] on 16 September. On 13 September, Lai had shared a video to [[WeChat]] and Facebook, which showed scenery around his home town and used the song as its background music, with the caption \"This is my homeland, I want her to be free!\"<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u300c\u5357\u65b9\u8857\u982d\u904b\u52d5\u300d\u7dad\u6b0a\u4eba\u58eb\u6d89\u5c0b\u91c1\u6ecb\u4e8b\u88ab\u6355\u3000\u66fe\u5206\u4eab\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u6b4c\u66f2 |url=https://news.mingpao.com/ins/%E5%85%A9%E5%B2%B8/article/20190917/s00004/1568685795871/%E3%80%90%E9%80%83%E7%8A%AF%E6%A2%9D%E4%BE%8B%E3%80%91%E3%80%8C%E5%8D%97%E6%96%B9%E8%A1%97%E9%A0%AD%E9%81%8B%E5%8B%95%E3%80%8D%E7%B6%AD%E6%AC%8A%E4%BA%BA%E5%A3%AB%E6%B6%89%E5%B0%8B%E9%87%81%E6%BB%8B%E4%BA%8B%E8%A2%AB%E6%8D%95-%E6%9B%BE%E5%88%86%E4%BA%AB%E3%80%8A%E9%A1%98%E6%A6%AE%E5%85%89%E6%AD%B8%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E3%80%8B%E6%AD%8C%E6%9B%B2 |accessdate=18 September 2019 |work=Ming Pao |date=18 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923080529/https://news.mingpao.com/ins/%e5%85%a9%e5%b2%b8/article/20190917/s00004/1568685795871/%e3%80%90%e9%80%83%e7%8a%af%e6%a2%9d%e4%be%8b%e3%80%91%e3%80%8c%e5%8d%97%e6%96%b9%e8%a1%97%e9%a0%ad%e9%81%8b%e5%8b%95%e3%80%8d%e7%b6%ad%e6%ac%8a%e4%ba%ba%e5%a3%ab%e6%b6%89%e5%b0%8b%e9%87%81%e6%bb%8b%e4%ba%8b%e8%a2%ab%e6%8d%95-%e6%9b%be%e5%88%86%e4%ba%ab%e3%80%8a%e9%a1%98%e6%a6%ae%e5%85%89%e6%ad%b8%e9%a6%99%e6%b8%af%e3%80%8b%e6%ad%8c%e6%9b%b2 |archive-date=23 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=\u6c88\u71d5\u5a9a |script-title=zh:\u7a57\u7dad\u6b0a\u8005\u4e0a\u8f09\u300a\u69ae\u5149\u300b\u88ab\u6355 |url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20190918/20770339 |accessdate=18 September 2019 |work=Apple Daily |date=18 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924123619/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20190918/20770339 |archive-date=24 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2452818958098030&id=1466849490028320 |title=Lai Rifu has been criminally detained Suspected to be related to his video post of 'Glory to Hong Kong' |date=16 September 2019 |website=\u5357\u65b9\u50bb\u74dc\u5173\u6ce8\u7fa4 |publisher=Facebook |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190924123946/https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2452818958098030&id=1466849490028320 |archive-date=24 September 2019 |access-date=24 September 2019 |url-status=live }}{{Primary source inline|date=September 2019}}</ref> On 18 September, around 20 pro-democracy activists, including [[Civic Party]] legislator [[Kwok Ka-ki]], [[Civil Human Rights Front]] convener [[Jimmy Sham]] and members of the [[League of Social Democrats]] rallied to the Hong Kong Liaison Office, demanding the release of Lai. The activists chanted slogans and sang the song outside the Liaison Office's entrance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1481237-20190918.htm |title=Activists rally over Guangzhou dissident's arrest |date=18 September 2019 |website=RTHK English News |access-date=24 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924123619/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1481237-20190918.htm |archive-date=24 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u6cdb\u6c11\u4e2d\u806f\u8fa6\u5916\u5531\u53cd\u4fee\u4f8b\u6b4c \u8072\u63f4\u8cf4\u65e5\u798f |url=https://www2.hkej.com/instantnews/current/article/2253281/%E6%B3%9B%E6%B0%91%E4%B8%AD%E8%81%AF%E8%BE%A6%E5%A4%96%E5%94%B1%E5%8F%8D%E4%BF%AE%E4%BE%8B%E6%AD%8C+%E8%81%B2%E6%8F%B4%E8%B3%B4%E6%97%A5%E7%A6%8F |accessdate=19 September 2019 |work=Hong Kong Economic Journal |date=18 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924123629/https://www2.hkej.com/instantnews/current/article/2253281/%25E6%25B3%259B%25E6%25B0%2591%25E4%25B8%25AD%25E8%2581%25AF%25E8%25BE%25A6%25E5%25A4%2596%25E5%2594%25B1%25E5%258F%258D%25E4%25BF%25AE%25E4%25BE%258B%25E6%25AD%258C%2B%25E8%2581%25B2%25E6%258F%25B4%25E8%25B3%25B4%25E6%2597%25A5%25E7%25A6%258F |archive-date=24 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Copyright infringement by secondary creations ===\n[[File:Orchestra_playing_Glory_to_Hong_Kong.png|thumb|right|Orchestra playing the march Glory to Hong Kong<ref>{{Citation|script-title=zh:\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u7ba1\u5f26\u6a02\u5718\u53ca\u5408\u5531\u5718\u7248 MV|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oUIDL4SB60g|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914063810/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oUIDL4SB60g|archive-date=14 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>.]]\n\nOn 12 September, a video titled \"Glory to Hong Kong (Police Version MV)\" (Chinese: \u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b\u8b66\u5bdf\u7248MV) appeared on YouTube. It uses the original song and lyrics in audio, paired with scenes of [[Hong Kong Police Force|Hong Kong Police]] using [[tear gas]] and other [[crowd control|crowd-control]] weapons on protesters. On the screen, however, the lyrics \"Revolution of our Times\" were replaced with \"Mission of the Police\". Since being uploaded, this MV had received criticism from [[netizen]]s which were removed later that night. Timelapse photographer Francis So condemned the MV on his Facebook page, stating that the timelapse of the night view of Hong Kong near the end of the video infringes his copyright. [[Hong Kong Cable Television|Cable TV]] also made a statement regarding clips from [[I-CABLE News Channel (Hong Kong)|i-CABLE News]] used in the video, saying that they would retain the right to pursue all [[copyright infringement]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/realtime/article/20190913/60039445|script-title=zh:\u3010\u9006\u6b0a\u904b\u52d5\u3011\u85cd\u7d72\u5077\u6b4c\u5077\u7247\u88fd\u8b66\u7248\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f\u300b \u4f5c\u66f2\u4eba\uff1a\u671f\u5f85\u9ec3\u85cd\u5927\u5408\u5531|website=Apple Daily|language=zh-han|url-status=live|access-date=29 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912221556/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/realtime/article/20190913/60039445|archive-date=12 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%e6%b8%af%e8%81%9e/article/20190913/s00002/1568313586976/%e3%80%90emily%e3%80%91%e3%80%8a%e9%a1%98%e6%a6%ae%e5%85%89%e3%80%8b%e8%ad%a6%e5%af%9f%e7%89%88mv%e8%a2%ab%e6%8c%87%e4%be%b5%e6%ac%8a|script-title=zh:\u3010Emily\u3011\u300a\u9858\u69ae\u5149\u300b\u8b66\u5bdf\u7248MV\u88ab\u6307\u4fb5\u6b0a \u2013 20190913 \u2013 \u6e2f\u805e|website=[[Ming Pao]]|language=zh-hant|url-status=live|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing this incident, another video titled \"May Truth be Bestowed Upon Hong Kong\" (Chinese: \u9858\u771f\u7406\u6551\u9999\u6e2f) appeared. It used the instrumentals of \"Glory to Hong Kong\", but lyrics were rewritten by someone under the pseudonym \"a person who loves Hong Kong\" (Chinese: \u611b\u6e2f\u7684\u4eba) to praise the Hong Kong Police Force and to fight against \"rioters\". [[Lin Xi]] made a remark stating that the use of instrumentals from the original \"did not give a sense of violation, and was like a match made in heaven\". He opined that the problem was the definition of \"rioters, whether they were those who abused their power to arrest and beat up people or the powerless force that was attempting to fight back\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hk.lifestyle.appledaily.com/lifestyle/columnist/\u6797\u5915/daily/article/20190916/20768801|script-title=zh:\u85cd\u7d72\u4e8c\u5275\u300a\u69ae\u5149\u300b\u6b4c\u8a5e\u5beb\u5f97\u597d \u2013 \u6797\u5915|website=Apple Daily|language=zh-han|url-status=live|access-date=29 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929064145/https://hk.lifestyle.appledaily.com/lifestyle/columnist/%E6%9E%97%E5%A4%95/daily/article/20190916/20768801/|archive-date=29 September 2019}}</ref> This MV was reuploaded to [[Sina Weibo]] by various Chinese communist official organisations, such as ''[[People's Daily]]'' and the [[Communist Youth League of China|Communist Youth League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weibo.com/3937348351/I6T9p8LE5|script-title=zh:\u613f\u771f\u7406\u6551\u9999\u6e2f\uff01\u8fd9\u662f\u6211\u4eec\u5171\u540c\u7684\u5fc3\u58f0|date=14 September 2019|website=\u65b0\u6d6a\u5fae\u535a Sina Weibo|publisher=Communist Youth League China|language=zh-simp|url-status=live|access-date=29 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929064115/https://www.weibo.com/3937348351/I6T9p8LE5|archive-date=29 September 2019}}{{Primary source inline|date=October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weibo.com/2803301701/I6SD0DSPE|script-title=zh:\u4e00\u8d77\u8f6c\u53d1\u8fd9\u9996\u6b4c\uff0c\u613f\u771f\u7406\u6551\u9999\u6e2f|date=14 September 2019|website=\u65b0\u6d6a\u5fae\u535a Sina Weibo|agency=\u4eba\u6c11\u65e5\u62a5 People Daily|language=zh-simp|url-status=live|access-date=29 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929064106/https://www.weibo.com/2803301701/I6SD0DSPE|archive-date=29 September 2019}}{{Primary source inline|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 September, the 5th anniversary of the [[Umbrella Movement]], a YouTube channel named \"Channel Me\" uploaded a video titled \"Peace Upon Hong Kong\" (Chinese: \u9858\u5e73\u5b89\u6b78\u9999\u6e2f). It was a video spoof of the orchestral MV of \"Glory to Hong Kong\" by Black Blorchestra. It was also re-uploaded to other social media, including [[Junius Ho]]'s Facebook page. All uploads of this song were later disabled by [[Content ID (system)|Content ID]] claims by [[Denise Ho]]'s label Goomusic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3030798/youtube-pulls-down-video-spoof-protest-anthem-glory-hong|title=YouTube pulls down video spoof of protest anthem 'Glory to Hong Kong'|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=29 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929051331/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3030798/youtube-pulls-down-video-spoof-protest-anthem-glory-hong|archive-date=29 September 2019|url-status=live|date=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* \"[[Do You Hear the People Sing?]]\"\n* \"[[We Shall Overcome]]\"\n* \"[[Sing Hallelujah to the Lord]]\"\n* \"[[El pueblo unido jam\u00e1s ser\u00e1 vencido]]\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist\n|refs=<ref name=time>{{cite news|title=Listen to the Song That Hong Kong's Youthful Protesters Are Calling Their 'National Anthem'|first=Hillary|last=Leung|url=https://time.com/5672018/glory-to-hong-kong-protests-national-anthem|work=Time|date=10 September 2019|access-date=10 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910165022/https://time.com/5672018/glory-to-hong-kong-protests-national-anthem/|archive-date=10 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=Hong Kong Protesters, Without an Anthem to Sing, Create One Online|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/12/world/asia/glory-to-hong-kong-anthem.html|first=Daniel|last=Victor|date=12 September 2019|journal=The New York Times|access-date=13 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913015809/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/12/world/asia/glory-to-hong-kong-anthem.html|archive-date=13 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"scmp\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3026609/protesters-newest-theme-song-glory-hong-kong-echoes-through|title=Protesters' latest theme song, 'Glory to Hong Kong', rings out in malls|first1=Yujing|last1=Liu|first2=Ng|last2=Kang-chung|first3=Sidney|last3=Leng|journal=South China Morning Post|date=11 September 2019|access-date=10 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910174355/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3026609/protesters-newest-theme-song-glory-hong-kong-echoes-through|archive-date=10 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AutoK9-1\">{{Cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oUIDL4SB60g|script-title=zh:\u300