{"title_page": "Laura Harrier", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Laura Harrier\n| image              = Laura Harrier Cannes 2018 2.jpg\n| caption            = Harrier at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]].\n| birth_name         = <!-- Do NOT add unless sourced to a [[WP:RS]] -->\nLaura Ruth Harrier\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1990|3|28}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[William Esper Studio]]\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*model\n}}\n| yearsactive        = 2013\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Laura Ruth Harrier'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5637553/|title=Laura Harrier|website=IMDb|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B19ityegF54/|title=LAURA HARRIER\u2019s Instagram post: \u201cbaby laura\u2019s first modeling card \ud83d\udc7c\ud83c\udffd i think i was 14? i was so self conscious because i had recently tripped and fell and my lip got\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> (born March 28, 1990<ref name=Elle>{{cite web |author=Chang, Mahalia |date=July 3, 2017 |url=http://www.elle.com.au/celebrity/laura-harrier-spiderman-facts-13641 |title=Everything You Need To Know About \u2018Spider-Man\u2019 Babe, Laura Harrier |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]}}</ref>) is an American actress and former model. Harrier was first recognized for her portrayal of [[Destiny Evans]] in the short-lived reboot of the American [[soap opera]] ''[[One Life to Live]]'' in 2013. In 2017, she made her major film debut portraying [[Liz Allan]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Laura Harrier confirmed in July 2017 in an interview with ''Total Film'' that the character goes by her mother's maiden name \"Allan\" within the Marvel Cinematic Universe, and that the character would become [[Firestar (comics)|Firestar]] in a future film.</ref> in ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Anderson, Ethan|date=July 25, 2016|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/spider-man-homecoming-characters/|title=Spider-Man Homecoming Characters Revealed|publisher=[[/Film]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/spider-man-homecoming-casts-laura-harrier-from-one-life-to-live-exclusive/|title='Spider-Man: Homecoming' Casts Laura Harrier From 'One Life to Live' (Exclusive)|publisher=[[TheWrap]]|author=Geier, Thom|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/tony-revolori-and-laura-harrier-join-spider-man-homecoming-1201754866/|title=Tony Revolori and Laura Harrier Join 'Spider-Man: Homecoming'|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=April 16, 2016|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHarrier was born March 28, 1990<ref name=Elle/> in Chicago, Illinois,<ref name=ABCChicago>{{cite web|url=http://abc7chicago.com/entertainment/laura-harrier-star-of-spiderman-homecoming-returns-to-chicago/2127314/|title=Laura Harrier, star of 'Spiderman: Homecoming' returns to Chicago|date=June 21, 2017|publisher=[[WLS-TV]]}}</ref> and was raised in [[Evanston, Illinois]].<ref name=ABCChicago/> She is biracial with an African-American father and a Caucasian mother.<ref name=TheCut>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2017/07/laura-harrier-of-spider-man-homecoming-interviewed.html|title=Laughing and Crying With Laura Harrier, the New Star of ''Spider-Man''|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|The Cut]]|author=Weatherford, Ashley|date=July 5, 2017}}</ref> She attended [[Evanston Township High School]] from 2004 to 2008. Her father works in insurance and her mother is a speech pathologist.<ref name=Interview>{{cite web|author=Ortved, John|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/laura-harrier/|title=Laura Harrier|magazine=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> She has one younger brother.<ref name=TheCut/>\n\nHarrier left home for New York at age 18 to attend the [[New York University]] [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]]. Upon arrival, Harrier fell into modeling and deferred enrollment to the university.<ref name=TheCut/> Eventually, she decided that she wanted to pursue acting and attended [[William Esper Studio]] acting school in New York City.<ref name=Interview/><ref name=TheCut/>\n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\nHarrier appeared in the reboot of American soap opera ''[[One Life to Live]]'' (2013) as Destiny Evans. She has also been in projects such as ''[[The Last Five Years]]'' (2014) and ''[[4th Man Out]]'' (2016).\n\nHarrier had her major film debut playing [[Peter Parker]]'s one-time love interest [[Liz Allan]] in ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]'' (2017). In June 2017, it was announced that Harrier would be portraying Millie Montag in HBO's film adaptation of acclaimed novel ''[[Fahrenheit 451]]'', opposite [[Michael B. Jordan]];<ref name=\"F451_1\">{{cite web|author=Petski, Denise|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/fahrenheit-451-laura-harrier-cast-millie-hbo-movie-1202120406/amp/|title='Fahrenheit 451': Laura Harrier Cast As Millie In HBO Movie |publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=June 2017}}</ref> however, she was later cut from the film.<ref name=\"F451_2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/blackkklansman-star-laura-harrier-going-spider-mans-homecoming-cannes-red-carpet/|title=\u2018BlacKkKlansman\u2019 Star Laura Harrier on Going From Spider-Man\u2019s Homecoming to Cannes Red Carpet|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Steve|last=Pond|date=May 9, 2018|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> Harrier co-starred as a civil rights activist in the thriller film ''[[BlacKkKlansman]]'' (2018), opposite [[John David Washington]], [[Adam Driver]], and [[Topher Grace]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Alessandro|first1=Anthony|title=Adam Driver Joins Spike Lee\u2019s \u2018Black Klansman\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/adam-driver-spike-lee-black-klansman-1202194537/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=18 May 2018|date=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Harrier starred in ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]'', opposite [[Bria Vinaite]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/laura-harrier-bria-vinaite-lily-newmark-board-balance-not-symmetry-with-biffy-clyro-exclusive/5133310.article|title=Laura Harrier, Bria Vinaite, Lily Newmark board 'Balance, Not Symmetry' with Biffy Clyro (exclusive)|website=Screen International|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Modeling and fashion===\nHarrier has modelled for campaigns with companies such as [[Garnier]], [[Urban Outfitters]], [[American Eagle Outfitters|American Eagle]] and [[L'Or\u00e9al]], and has turned up on the pages of ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' and ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''.\n\nIn 2016, Harrier starred in \"The Realest Real\", a short film for luxury French fashion brand [[Kenzo (brand)|Kenzo]] directed by [[Carrie Brownstein]]. Harrier is currently part of [[Calvin Klein]] and [[Louis Vuitton]] campaigns and is an ambassador for luxury Italian jewelry brand [[Bvlgari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bulgari.com/en-us/magazine/jon-kortajarena-the-new-bulgari-global-watches-ambassador|title=Basel World|publisher=[[Bulgari]]|accessdate=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807235801/https://www.bulgari.com/en-us/magazine/jon-kortajarena-the-new-bulgari-global-watches-ambassador|archive-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHarrier has been dating American basketball player [[Klay Thompson]] since 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/everything-you-should-know-about-nba-star-klay-thompsons-girlfriend-laura-harrier.html/|title=Everything You Should Know About NBA Star Klay Thompson's Girlfriend Laura Harrier|last=Winifred|first=Dirk|last2=Articles|first2=More|date=2019-12-14|website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=December 14|first3=2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"| {{dagger|alt=Denotes films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n===Film and television===\n<!-- Please note: do NOT add \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=unsortable | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[One Life to Live]]''\n| [[Destiny Evans]]\n| 43 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Unforgettable''\n| Amber\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Last Five Years (film)|The Last Five Years]]''\n| Manuscript Woman\n| Film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Galyntine''\n| Wylie\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[4th Man Out]]''\n| Dorothy Cuda\n| Film\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''\n| [[Liz Allan]]\n| Film\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Fahrenheit 451 (2018 film)|Fahrenheit 451]]''\n| Millie Montag\n| Television film; deleted scenes<ref name=\"F451_1\" /><ref name=\"F451_2\" />\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[BlacKkKlansman]]''\n| Patrice\n| Film\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]''\n| Shirley-Caitlin Walker\n| Film\n|-\n|-\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Hollywood (American TV series)|Hollywood]]''{{dagger}}\n| Camille Washington\n| Post-production\n|-\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Bios (film)|Bios]]''{{dagger}}\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Post-production\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[The Starling]]''{{dagger}}\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Post-production\n|}<!--DO NOT ADD ANYTHING THAT ISN'T PRESENTLY FILMING OR IN POST-PRODUCTION PER [[WP:NFF]] AND [[WP:CRYSTAL]]-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Eckardt, Stephanie (2017 June). \"Laura Harrier Isn't in Spider-Man: Homecoming Just to Look Pretty for Peter Parker\", ''W''. retrieved from https://www.wmagazine.com\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|5637553}}\n* {{Instagram|lauraharrier}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/laura-harrier-louis-vuitton-spiderman-paris-fashion-week-front-row|title=Spiderman\u2019s Laura Harrier Breaks Out in All Black at Louis Vuitton|publisher=}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harrier, Laura}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Female models from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Evanston Township High School alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name            = Laura Harrier\n| image           = Laura Harrier Cannes 2018 2.jpg\n| caption         = Harrier at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]].\n| birth_name      = <!-- Do NOT add unless sourced to a [[WP:RS]] -->\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1990|3|28}}\n| birth_place     = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| alma_mater      = [[William Esper Studio]]\n| occupation      = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*model\n}}\n| yearsactive     = 2013\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Laura Harrier''' (born March 28, 1990<ref name=Elle>{{cite web |author=Chang, Mahalia |date=July 3, 2017 |url=http://www.elle.com.au/celebrity/laura-harrier-spiderman-facts-13641 |title=Everything You Need To Know About \u2018Spider-Man\u2019 Babe, Laura Harrier |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]}}</ref>) is an American actress and former model. Harrier was first recognized for her portrayal of [[Destiny Evans]] in the short-lived reboot of the American [[soap opera]] ''[[One Life to Live]]'' in 2013. In 2017, she made her major film debut portraying [[Liz Allan]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Laura Harrier confirmed in July 2017 in an interview with ''Total Film'' that the character goes by her mother's maiden name \"Allan\" within the Marvel Cinematic Universe, and that the character would become [[Firestar (comics)|Firestar]] in a future film.</ref> in ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Anderson, Ethan|date=July 25, 2016|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/spider-man-homecoming-characters/|title=Spider-Man Homecoming Characters Revealed|publisher=[[/Film]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/spider-man-homecoming-casts-laura-harrier-from-one-life-to-live-exclusive/|title='Spider-Man: Homecoming' Casts Laura Harrier From 'One Life to Live' (Exclusive)|publisher=[[TheWrap]]|author=Geier, Thom|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/tony-revolori-and-laura-harrier-join-spider-man-homecoming-1201754866/|title=Tony Revolori and Laura Harrier Join 'Spider-Man: Homecoming'|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=April 16, 2016|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHarrier was born March 28, 1990<ref name=Elle/> in Chicago, Illinois,<ref name=ABCChicago>{{cite web|url=http://abc7chicago.com/entertainment/laura-harrier-star-of-spiderman-homecoming-returns-to-chicago/2127314/|title=Laura Harrier, star of 'Spiderman: Homecoming' returns to Chicago|date=June 21, 2017|publisher=[[WLS-TV]]}}</ref> and was raised in [[Evanston, Illinois]].<ref name=ABCChicago/> She is biracial with an African-American father and a Caucasian mother.<ref name=TheCut>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2017/07/laura-harrier-of-spider-man-homecoming-interviewed.html|title=Laughing and Crying With Laura Harrier, the New Star of ''Spider-Man''|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|The Cut]]|author=Weatherford, Ashley|date=July 5, 2017}}</ref> She attended [[Evanston Township High School]] from 2004 to 2008. Her father works in insurance and her mother is a speech pathologist.<ref name=Interview>{{cite web|author=Ortved, John|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/laura-harrier/|title=Laura Harrier|magazine=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> She has one younger brother.<ref name=TheCut/>\n\nHarrier left home for New York at age 18 to attend the [[New York University]] [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]]. Upon arrival, Harrier fell into modeling and deferred enrollment to the university.<ref name=TheCut/> Eventually, she decided that she wanted to pursue acting and attended [[William Esper Studio]] acting school in New York City.<ref name=Interview/><ref name=TheCut/>\n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\nHarrier appeared in the reboot of American soap opera ''[[One Life to Live]]'' (2013) as Destiny Evans. She has also been in projects such as ''[[The Last Five Years]]'' (2014) and ''[[4th Man Out]]'' (2016).\n\nHarrier had her major film debut playing [[Peter Parker]]'s one-time love interest [[Liz Allan]] in ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]'' (2017). In June 2017, it was announced that Harrier would be portraying Millie Montag in HBO's film adaptation of acclaimed novel ''[[Fahrenheit 451]]'', opposite [[Michael B. Jordan]];<ref name=\"F451_1\">{{cite web|author=Petski, Denise|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/fahrenheit-451-laura-harrier-cast-millie-hbo-movie-1202120406/amp/|title='Fahrenheit 451': Laura Harrier Cast As Millie In HBO Movie |publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=June 2017}}</ref> however, she was later cut from the film.<ref name=\"F451_2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/blackkklansman-star-laura-harrier-going-spider-mans-homecoming-cannes-red-carpet/|title=\u2018BlacKkKlansman\u2019 Star Laura Harrier on Going From Spider-Man\u2019s Homecoming to Cannes Red Carpet|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Steve|last=Pond|date=May 9, 2018|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> Harrier co-starred as a civil rights activist in the thriller film ''[[BlacKkKlansman]]'' (2018), opposite [[John David Washington]], [[Adam Driver]], and [[Topher Grace]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Alessandro|first1=Anthony|title=Adam Driver Joins Spike Lee\u2019s \u2018Black Klansman\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/adam-driver-spike-lee-black-klansman-1202194537/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=18 May 2018|date=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Harrier starred in ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]'', opposite [[Bria Vinaite]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/laura-harrier-bria-vinaite-lily-newmark-board-balance-not-symmetry-with-biffy-clyro-exclusive/5133310.article|title=Laura Harrier, Bria Vinaite, Lily Newmark board 'Balance, Not Symmetry' with Biffy Clyro (exclusive)|website=Screen International|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Modeling and fashion===\nHarrier has modelled for campaigns with companies such as [[Garnier]], [[Urban Outfitters]], [[American Eagle Outfitters|American Eagle]] and [[L'Or\u00e9al]], and has turned up on the pages of ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' and ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''.\n\nIn 2016, Harrier starred in \"The Realest Real\", a short film for luxury French fashion brand [[Kenzo (brand)|Kenzo]] directed by [[Carrie Brownstein]]. Harrier is currently part of [[Calvin Klein]] and [[Louis Vuitton]] campaigns and is an ambassador for luxury Italian jewelry brand [[Bvlgari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bulgari.com/en-us/magazine/jon-kortajarena-the-new-bulgari-global-watches-ambassador|title=Basel World|publisher=[[Bulgari]]|accessdate=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807235801/https://www.bulgari.com/en-us/magazine/jon-kortajarena-the-new-bulgari-global-watches-ambassador|archive-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHarrier has been dating American basketball player [[Klay Thompson]] since 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/everything-you-should-know-about-nba-star-klay-thompsons-girlfriend-laura-harrier.html/|title=Everything You Should Know About NBA Star Klay Thompson's Girlfriend Laura Harrier|last=Winifred|first=Dirk|last2=Articles|first2=More|date=2019-12-14|website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=December 14|first3=2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"| {{dagger|alt=Denotes films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n===Film and television===\n<!-- Please note: do NOT add \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=unsortable | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[One Life to Live]]''\n| [[Destiny Evans]]\n| 43 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Unforgettable''\n| Amber\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Last Five Years (film)|The Last Five Years]]''\n| Manuscript Woman\n| Film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Galyntine''\n| Wylie\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[4th Man Out]]''\n| Dorothy Cuda\n| Film\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''\n| [[Liz Allan]]\n| Film\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Fahrenheit 451 (2018 film)|Fahrenheit 451]]''\n| Millie Montag\n| Television film; deleted scenes<ref name=\"F451_1\" /><ref name=\"F451_2\" />\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[BlacKkKlansman]]''\n| Patrice\n| Film\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]''\n| Shirley-Caitlin Walker\n| Film\n|-\n|-\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Hollywood (American TV series)|Hollywood]]''{{dagger}}\n| Camille Washington\n| Post-production\n|-\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Bios (film)|Bios]]''{{dagger}}\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Post-production\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[The Starling]]''{{dagger}}\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Post-production\n|}<!--DO NOT ADD ANYTHING THAT ISN'T PRESENTLY FILMING OR IN POST-PRODUCTION PER [[WP:NFF]] AND [[WP:CRYSTAL]]-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Eckardt, Stephanie (2017 June). \"Laura Harrier Isn't in Spider-Man: Homecoming Just to Look Pretty for Peter Parker\", ''W''. retrieved from https://www.wmagazine.com\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|5637553}}\n* {{Instagram|lauraharrier}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/laura-harrier-louis-vuitton-spiderman-paris-fashion-week-front-row|title=Spiderman\u2019s Laura Harrier Breaks Out in All Black at Louis Vuitton|publisher=}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harrier, Laura}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Female models from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Evanston Township High School alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Factfanatic1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Her middle name was missing. I added sources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laura_Harrier"}
{"title_page": "University of Florida Health", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = University of Florida Health\n| logo                = UFHealth logo.png\n| logo_size           = 200px\n| type                = Private ([[not-for-profit]])\n| foundation          = 1958\n| location            = [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]], [[Florida]]<br>[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], [[Florida]]\n| key_people          = Edward Jimenez, M.B.A. - Chief Executive Officer <br>Daniel R. Wilson, M.D., Ph.D. - Senior Vice President for Academic Affairs, Chairman of the Board of Directors\n| area_served         = [[Northeast Florida]], [[North Central Florida]]\n| industry            = [[Health care]]\n| services            = tertiary level clinical care<br>rehabilitation<br>cancer centers<br>community medical facilities<br>pediatrics care<br>psychiatric care\n| revenue             = {{gain}}120 million [[USD]] (FY 2012)<ref>{{cite web|title=Shands Teaching Hospital and  Clinics, Inc. and Subsidiaries Consolidated Basic Financial Statements, Required Supplementary Information and  Supplemental Consolidating Information June 30, 2012 and 2011|url=https://ufhealth.org/sites/default/files/media/Health-Images/audited_financial_statements_FY_2012.pdf|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n| num_employees       = 22,000 (2013) <ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to UF Health|url=https://ufhealth.org/welcome-uf-health|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n| divisions           = Patient Care<br>Education<br>Research\n| footnotes           = affiliated university = [[University of Florida College of Medicine]]\n| operating_income    = \n| net_income          = \n| subsid              = \n| homepage            = {{URL|https://ufhealth.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''University of Florida Health''' ('''UF Health''') is a medical network associated with the [[University of Florida]]. It includes two academic hospitals \u2013 [[UF Health Shands Hospital]] in [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] and [[UF Health Jacksonville]] \u2013 and several other hospitals and facilities in [[North Florida]]. It used to be known as '''Shands Healthcare''' and '''UF&Shands'''.<ref name=Patton>{{cite news |title= Shands Jacksonville renamed UF Health Jacksonville |author= Charlie Patton |url= http://jacksonville.com/news/health-and-fitness/2013-05-20/story/shands-jacksonville-renamed-uf-health-jacksonville |newspaper= [[The Florida Times-Union]] |date= May 20, 2013 |accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref> The network was named to the [[U.S. News & World Report]]'s 2015 list of the nation's top 50 hospitals.<ref>[http://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/fl/shands-at-the-university-of-florida-6390283 U.S. News & World Report: America\u2019s Best Hospitals 2015]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[William A. Shands]] was a Florida state Senator, elected from the 32nd District in the mid-1940s. Shands was recruited to the effort to create a teaching hospital in the [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] area, though he at first considered that a larger city might be a better site, and was instrumental in obtaining state funding. In 1956, the University of Florida [[University of Florida College of Medicine|Colleges of Medicine]] and [[University of Florida College of Nursing|Nursing]] opened; in 1958, the UF Teaching Hospital followed. It was renamed in 1965 to recognize Shands's efforts to ''W. A. Shands Teaching Hospital and Clinics''.<ref>[http://www.shands.org/about/history.asp Shands website: Shands HealthCare History ]</ref> The institution later became Shands Hospital, part of the Shands HealthCare network.\n\nIn 1969, the UF College of Medicine established a satellite campus in [[Jacksonville]] at Duval Medical Center; this was renamed University Hospital in 1971. In 1999, both University Hospital and another Jacksonville hospital, Methodist Medical Center, were merged into Shands HealthCare as Shands Jacksonville, which included a hospital, associated clinics and the university campus. The complex was renamed [[UF Health at Jacksonville]] in 2013, with the hospital itself being named UF Health Jacksonville.<ref name=Patton/>\n\nThe UF network purchased Alachua General Hospital in east Gainesville from Santa Fe Health Care in 1996, changing the name to Shands AGH. Prior to being purchased by Santa Fe in 1983, AGH was owned by the county.<ref>Swirko, Cindy: [http://www.gainesville.com/article/20090415/ARTICLES/904151015?Title=County-to-hold-meeting-on-AGH \"County to hold meeting on AGH\"] Gainesville Sun, April 15, 2009</ref> On Nov. 1, 2009, Shands HealthCare closed Shands AGH due to budget cuts.<ref>Chun, Diane: [http://www.gainesville.com/article/20091028/ARTICLES/910289873?Title=The-end-of-an-era-Shands-AGH-closes-on-Sunday \"The end of an era: Shands AGH closes on Sunday\"] Gainesville Sun, October 28, 2009</ref> The system simultaneously opened a cancer hospital south of its main location on the UF campus.\n\nThe network was renamed University of Florida Health in May 2013.<ref name=Patton/> University of Florida Health comprises multiple distinct legal entities, the largest being UF Heath Shands Gainesville and UF Health Jacksonville<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://ufhealth.org/uf-health-leadership|title=UF Health Leadership|date=2012-05-17|website=UF Health, University of Florida Health|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>. \n\nIn 2020 UF Health acquired two new hospitals, The Villages\u00ae Regional and Leesburg Regional <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://ufhealth.org/uf-health-leesburg-hospital|title=UF Health Leesburg Hospital|last=Leesburg|first=600 E. Dixie Ave|last2=Fl 34748|date=2019-12-23|website=UF Health, University of Florida Health|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://ufhealth.org/uf-health-villages-hospital|title=UF Health The Villages\u00ae Hospital|last=Villages|first=1451 El Camino Real The|last2=Fl 32159|date=2019-12-23|website=UF Health, University of Florida Health|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n[[Image:J Hillis Miller HSC.jpg|250px|right|thumb|The Gainesville campus of [[J. Hillis Miller Health Science Center|Miller Health Science Center]] ]]\nThe following [[Tertiary referral hospital|tertiary]] facilities represent the core of UF Health's academic, teaching, trauma, specialty and research-related hospitals. With campuses in Gainesville and Jacksonville, UF Health includes six health colleges, six research institutes, two teaching hospitals, two specialty hospitals, a community hospital, and a host of physician medical practices and outpatient services throughout north central and northeast Florida.\n\n===Health Science Center Gainesville===\nLocated at UF's main campus, the center encompasses six health colleges, six research institutes, three specialty hospitals and a teaching hospital. UF Health Cancer Center, Clinical and Translational Science Institute, [[Emerging Pathogens Institute]], [[University of Florida Cancer and Genetics Research Complex|Genetics Institute]], Institute on Aging and [[McKnight Brain Institute]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=55 cellspacing=5 style=\"float:center; margin:9px; border:1px solid;\"\n!colspan=\"20\" bgcolor=\"blue\" |HSC Colleges (Gainesville)\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Dentistry|College of Dentistry]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Public Health and Health Professions|College of Public Health and Health Professions]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Medicine|College of Medicine]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Nursing|College of Nursing]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Pharmacy|College of Pharmacy]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Veterinary Medicine|College of Veterinary Medicine]]\n|}\n[[File:Shands Childrens and Cancer Hospitals at Sunset.jpg|thumb|252x252px|The Cancer Hospital (left) and Children's Hospital (right) as seen from the top of parking garage 10. ]]\n\n* '''[[UF Health Shands Hospital]]''' is the flagship [[teaching hospital]] of the [[University of Florida]].  The hospital is a [[Level I trauma center]] and a leading [[Organ transplant|organ-transplant]] center. It houses 425-beds<ref>{{cite web|title=UF Health Shands|url=https://ufhealth.org/sites/default/files/media/fact-sheets/2018-uf-health-shands-fact-sheet.pdf|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n* '''UF Health Shands Children\u2019s Hospital''', housing 208 beds<ref>{{cite web|title=UF Health Shands Children's Hospital|url=https://ufhealth.org/sites/default/files/media/fact-sheets/2018-uf-health-shands-childrens-hospital-fact-sheet.pdf\n|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> and the pediatric emergency department. It is located in the same building as UF Health Shands Adult Hospital.\n* '''[[University of Florida Cancer Hospital|UF Health Shands Cancer Hospital]]''', housing 192 beds<ref>{{cite web|title=UF Health Shands Cancer Hospital|url=https://ufhealth.org/health-system-facts-and-figures|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> as well as the adult emergency department and a cancer research center. \n* '''[[University of Florida Neuromedicine Hospital|UF Health Shands Neuromedicine Hospital]]''', housing 160 beds. While it is a separate entity, it is located in the same building as the Heart and Vascular Hospital. \n*'''UF Health Heart and Vascular Hospital,''' housing 120 beds\n\nAn new hotel for family and outpatients is also being constructed immediately south of the Cancer and Neuromedicine buildings <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gainesville.com/news/20181102/uf-health-builds-32m-hotel-for-patient-families-outpatients|title=UF Health builds $32M hotel for patient families, outpatients|last=Smithson|first=Daniel|website=Gainesville Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>. All five hospitals, as well as the nearby VA hospital, are connected either at ground level or by basement level, allowing patients to be transported more easily.  \n\n=== Other Gainesville Locations ===\nThis list is incomplete and does not include all outpatient locations. UF Health offers outpatient pharmacies, primary care, specialty care, medical labs, and dental facilities in Gainesville, FL. <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://ufhealth.org/locations|title=Find a Location|website=UF Health, University of Florida Health|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n*'''UF Health Shands Rehab Hospita'''l housing 40 beds. It houses patients in rehabilitation for those recovering from strokes, traumatic injuries, and other conditions that interfere with activities of daily living. Not to be confused with the Florida Recovery Center, which provides substance abuse rehabilitation. \n*'''UF Health Shands Psychiatric Hospital''' housing 81 beds. This includes it's subsidiary the UF Health Florida Recovery Center.\n*'''UF Health Springhill Emergency Center'''\n*'''UF Health Kanapaha Emergency Center'''\n*'''UF Health ORTHOCare Orthopedics Ceter'''\n*'''UF Health Small Animal Hospital'''\n*'''UF Health Large Animal Hospital'''\n\n===Health Science Center Jacksonville===\nJacksonville is home to a large and important regional campus of UF Health, including three colleges, the UF Proton Therapy Institute, and the UF Health Jacksonville and UF Health North hospitals.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=55 cellspacing=5 style=\"float:center; margin:9px; border:1px solid;\"\n!colspan=\"20\" bgcolor=\"blue\" |HSC Colleges (Jacksonville)\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Medicine-Jacksonville|College of Medicine]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Nursing|College of Nursing]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Pharmacy|College of Pharmacy]]\n|}\n* '''[[UF Health Jacksonville]]''' is a regional [[teaching hospital]] of the [[University of Florida]].  The 695-bed<ref>{{cite web|title=UF Health Jacksonville |url=https://ufhealth.org/sites/default/files/media/fact-sheets/2018-uf-health-jacksonville-fact-sheet.pdf|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> hospital is a [[Level I trauma center]].\n* '''UF Health North''' is a 92-bed<ref>{{cite web|title=UF Health Jacksonville  North|url=https://ufhealth.org/sites/default/files/media/fact-sheets/2018-uf-health-ufhn-fact-sheet.pdf|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> community hospital and outpatient complex in North Jacksonville.\n\n===Other facilities===\n*UF Health Leesburg<ref name=\":1\" />\n*UF Health The Villages <ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShands Healthcare sold its community hospitals (Shands Lake Shore, Shands Live Oak, and Shands Starke) on July 1, 2010, to Health Management Associates. In 2020 UF Health acquired two new hospitals, Leesburg Regional Medical Center and The Villages\u00ae Regional Hospital <ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.shandslakeshore.com/ Shands Lake Shore]\n*[http://www.shandsliveoak.com/ Shands Live Oak]\n*[http://www.shandsstarke.com/ Shands Starke]\n*[http://ufhealthjax.org/ UF Health Jacksonville]\n*[http://north.ufhealthjax.org/ UF Health North]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/shands-university-florida UF Health Shands Hospital]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/shands-cancer-hospital-uf UF Health Shands Cancer Hospital]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/shands-hospital-children-uf UF Health Shands Children\u2019s Hospital]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/shands-vista UF Health Shands Psychiatric Hospital]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/shands-rehab-hospital UF Health Shands Rehab Hospital]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/uf-health-shands-homecare UF Health Shands HomeCare]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/locations University of Florida Physician Practices]\n*[https://ufhealth.org/search/locations/rehabilitation UF Health Shands Rehab Centers]\n\n{{University of Florida}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital networks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Health care companies established in 1958]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Florida]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Florida]]\n[[Category:1958 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organizations based in Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = University of Florida Health\n| logo                = UFHealth logo.png\n| logo_size           = 200px\n| type                = Private ([[not-for-profit]])\n| foundation          = 1958\n| location            = [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]], [[Florida]]<br>[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], [[Florida]]\n| key_people          = Edward Jimenez, M.B.A. - Chief Executive Officer <br>Daniel R. Wilson, M.D., Ph.D. - Senior Vice President for Academic Affairs, Chairman of the Board of Directors\n| area_served         = [[Northeast Florida]], [[North Central Florida]]\n| industry            = [[Health care]]\n| services            = tertiary level clinical care<br>rehabilitation<br>cancer centers<br>community medical facilities<br>pediatrics care<br>psychiatric care\n| revenue             = {{gain}}120 million [[USD]] (FY 2012)<ref>{{cite web|title=Shands Teaching Hospital and  Clinics, Inc. and Subsidiaries Consolidated Basic Financial Statements, Required Supplementary Information and  Supplemental Consolidating Information June 30, 2012 and 2011|url=https://ufhealth.org/sites/default/files/media/Health-Images/audited_financial_statements_FY_2012.pdf|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n| num_employees       = 22,000 (2013) <ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to UF Health|url=https://ufhealth.org/welcome-uf-health|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n| divisions           = Patient Care<br>Education<br>Research\n| footnotes           = affiliated university = [[University of Florida College of Medicine]]\n| operating_income    = \n| net_income          = \n| subsid              = \n| homepage            = {{URL|https://ufhealth.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''University of Florida Health''' ('''UF Health''') is a medical network associated with the [[University of Florida]]. It includes two academic hospitals \u2013 [[UF Health Shands Hospital]] in [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] and [[UF Health Jacksonville]] \u2013 and several other hospitals and facilities in [[North Florida]]. It used to be known as '''Shands Healthcare''' and '''UF&Shands'''.<ref name=Patton>{{cite news |title= Shands Jacksonville renamed UF Health Jacksonville |author= Charlie Patton |url= http://jacksonville.com/news/health-and-fitness/2013-05-20/story/shands-jacksonville-renamed-uf-health-jacksonville |newspaper= [[The Florida Times-Union]] |date= May 20, 2013 |accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref> The network was named to the [[U.S. News & World Report]]'s 2015 list of the nation's top 50 hospitals.<ref>[http://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/fl/shands-at-the-university-of-florida-6390283 U.S. News & World Report: America\u2019s Best Hospitals 2015]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[William A. Shands]] was a Florida state Senator, elected from the 32nd District in the mid-1940s. Shands was recruited to the effort to create a teaching hospital in the [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] area, though he at first considered that a larger city might be a better site, and was instrumental in obtaining state funding. In 1956, the University of Florida [[University of Florida College of Medicine|Colleges of Medicine]] and [[University of Florida College of Nursing|Nursing]] opened; in 1958, the UF Teaching Hospital followed. It was renamed in 1965 to recognize Shands's efforts to ''W. A. Shands Teaching Hospital and Clinics''.<ref>[http://www.shands.org/about/history.asp Shands website: Shands HealthCare History ]</ref> The institution later became Shands Hospital, part of the Shands HealthCare network.\n\nIn 1969, the UF College of Medicine established a satellite campus in [[Jacksonville]] at Duval Medical Center; this was renamed University Hospital in 1971. In 1999, both University Hospital and another Jacksonville hospital, Methodist Medical Center, were merged into Shands HealthCare as Shands Jacksonville, which included a hospital, associated clinics and the university campus. The complex was renamed [[UF Health at Jacksonville]] in 2013, with the hospital itself being named UF Health Jacksonville.<ref name=Patton/>\n\nThe UF network purchased Alachua General Hospital in east Gainesville from Santa Fe Health Care in 1996, changing the name to Shands AGH. Prior to being purchased by Santa Fe in 1983, AGH was owned by the county.<ref>Swirko, Cindy: [http://www.gainesville.com/article/20090415/ARTICLES/904151015?Title=County-to-hold-meeting-on-AGH \"County to hold meeting on AGH\"] Gainesville Sun, April 15, 2009</ref> On Nov. 1, 2009, Shands HealthCare closed Shands AGH due to budget cuts.<ref>Chun, Diane: [http://www.gainesville.com/article/20091028/ARTICLES/910289873?Title=The-end-of-an-era-Shands-AGH-closes-on-Sunday \"The end of an era: Shands AGH closes on Sunday\"] Gainesville Sun, October 28, 2009</ref> The system simultaneously opened a cancer hospital south of its main location on the UF campus.\n\nThe network was renamed University of Florida Health in May 2013.<ref name=Patton/> University of Florida Health comprises multiple distinct legal entities, the largest being UF Heath Shands Gainesville and UF Health Jacksonville<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://ufhealth.org/uf-health-leadership|title=UF Health Leadership|date=2012-05-17|website=UF Health, University of Florida Health|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>. \n\nIn 2020 UF Health acquired two new hospitals, The Villages\u00ae Regional and Leesburg Regional <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://ufhealth.org/uf-health-leesburg-hospital|title=UF Health Leesburg Hospital|last=Leesburg|first=600 E. Dixie Ave|last2=Fl 34748|date=2019-12-23|website=UF Health, University of Florida Health|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://ufhealth.org/uf-health-villages-hospital|title=UF Health The Villages\u00ae Hospital|last=Villages|first=1451 El Camino Real The|last2=Fl 32159|date=2019-12-23|website=UF Health, University of Florida Health|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n[[Image:J Hillis Miller HSC.jpg|250px|right|thumb|The Gainesville campus of [[J. Hillis Miller Health Science Center|Miller Health Science Center]] ]]\nThe following [[Tertiary referral hospital|tertiary]] facilities represent the core of UF Health's academic, teaching, trauma, specialty and research-related hospitals. With campuses in Gainesville and Jacksonville, UF Health includes six health colleges, six research institutes, two teaching hospitals, two specialty hospitals, a community hospital, and a host of physician medical practices and outpatient services throughout north central and northeast Florida.\n\n===Health Science Center Gainesville===\nLocated at UF's main campus, the center encompasses six health colleges, six research institutes, three specialty hospitals and a teaching hospital. UF Health Cancer Center, Clinical and Translational Science Institute, [[Emerging Pathogens Institute]], [[University of Florida Cancer and Genetics Research Complex|Genetics Institute]], Institute on Aging and [[McKnight Brain Institute]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=55 cellspacing=5 style=\"float:center; margin:9px; border:1px solid;\"\n!colspan=\"20\" bgcolor=\"blue\" |HSC Colleges (Gainesville)\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Dentistry|College of Dentistry]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Public Health and Health Professions|College of Public Health and Health Professions]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Medicine|College of Medicine]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Nursing|College of Nursing]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Pharmacy|College of Pharmacy]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Veterinary Medicine|College of Veterinary Medicine]]\n|}\n\n* '''[[UF Health Shands Hospital]]''' is the flagship [[teaching hospital]] of the [[University of Florida]].  The hospital is a [[Level I trauma center]] and a leading [[Organ transplant|organ-transplant]] center. It houses 425-beds<ref>{{cite web|title=UF Health Shands|url=https://ufhealth.org/sites/default/files/media/fact-sheets/2018-uf-health-shands-fact-sheet.pdf|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n* '''UF Health Shands Children\u2019s Hospital''', housing 208 beds<ref>{{cite web|title=UF Health Shands Children's Hospital|url=https://ufhealth.org/sites/default/files/media/fact-sheets/2018-uf-health-shands-childrens-hospital-fact-sheet.pdf\n|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> and the pediatric emergency department. It is located in the same building as UF Health Shands Adult Hospital.\n* '''[[University of Florida Cancer Hospital|UF Health Shands Cancer Hospital]]''', housing 192 beds<ref>{{cite web|title=UF Health Shands Cancer Hospital|url=https://ufhealth.org/health-system-facts-and-figures|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> as well as the adult emergency department and a cancer research center. \n* '''[[University of Florida Neuromedicine Hospital|UF Health Shands Neuromedicine Hospital]]''', housing 160 beds. While it is a separate entity, it is located in the same building as the Heart and Vascular Hospital. \n*'''UF Health Heart and Vascular Hospital,''' housing 120 beds\n\nAn new hotel for family and outpatients is also being constructed immediately south of the Cancer and Neuromedicine buildings <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gainesville.com/news/20181102/uf-health-builds-32m-hotel-for-patient-families-outpatients|title=UF Health builds $32M hotel for patient families, outpatients|last=Smithson|first=Daniel|website=Gainesville Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>. All five hospitals, as well as the nearby VA hospital, are connected either at ground level or by basement level, allowing patients to be transported more easily. \n\n=== Other Gainesville Locations ===\nThis list is incomplete and does not include all outpatient locations. UF Health offers outpatient pharmacies, primary care, specialty care, medical labs, and dental facilities in Gainesville, FL. <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://ufhealth.org/locations|title=Find a Location|website=UF Health, University of Florida Health|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n*'''UF Health Shands Rehab Hospita'''l housing 40 beds. It houses patients in rehabilitation for those recovering from strokes, traumatic injuries, and other conditions that interfere with activities of daily living. Not to be confused with the Florida Recovery Center, which provides substance abuse rehabilitation. \n*'''UF Health Shands Psychiatric Hospital''' housing 81 beds. This includes it's subsidiary the UF Health Florida Recovery Center.\n*'''UF Health Springhill Emergency Center'''\n*'''UF Health Kanapaha Emergency Center'''\n*'''UF Health ORTHOCare Orthopedics Ceter'''\n*'''UF Health Small Animal Hospital'''\n*'''UF Health Large Animal Hospital'''\n\n===Health Science Center Jacksonville===\nJacksonville is home to a large and important regional campus of UF Health, including three colleges, the UF Proton Therapy Institute, and the UF Health Jacksonville and UF Health North hospitals.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=55 cellspacing=5 style=\"float:center; margin:9px; border:1px solid;\"\n!colspan=\"20\" bgcolor=\"blue\" |HSC Colleges (Jacksonville)\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Medicine-Jacksonville|College of Medicine]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Nursing|College of Nursing]]\n|-\n| [[University of Florida College of Pharmacy|College of Pharmacy]]\n|}\n* '''[[UF Health Jacksonville]]''' is a regional [[teaching hospital]] of the [[University of Florida]].  The 695-bed<ref>{{cite web|title=UF Health Jacksonville |url=https://ufhealth.org/sites/default/files/media/fact-sheets/2018-uf-health-jacksonville-fact-sheet.pdf|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> hospital is a [[Level I trauma center]].\n* '''UF Health North''' is a 92-bed<ref>{{cite web|title=UF Health Jacksonville  North|url=https://ufhealth.org/sites/default/files/media/fact-sheets/2018-uf-health-ufhn-fact-sheet.pdf|publisher=UF Health|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> community hospital and outpatient complex in North Jacksonville.\n\n===Other facilities===\n*UF Health Leesburg<ref name=\":1\" />\n*UF Health The Villages <ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShands Healthcare sold its community hospitals (Shands Lake Shore, Shands Live Oak, and Shands Starke) on July 1, 2010, to Health Management Associates. In 2020 UF Health acquired two new hospitals, Leesburg Regional Medical Center and The Villages\u00ae Regional Hospital <ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.shandslakeshore.com/ Shands Lake Shore]\n*[http://www.shandsliveoak.com/ Shands Live Oak]\n*[http://www.shandsstarke.com/ Shands Starke]\n*[http://ufhealthjax.org/ UF Health Jacksonville]\n*[http://north.ufhealthjax.org/ UF Health North]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/shands-university-florida UF Health Shands Hospital]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/shands-cancer-hospital-uf UF Health Shands Cancer Hospital]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/shands-hospital-children-uf UF Health Shands Children\u2019s Hospital]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/shands-vista UF Health Shands Psychiatric Hospital]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/shands-rehab-hospital UF Health Shands Rehab Hospital]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/uf-health-shands-homecare UF Health Shands HomeCare]\n*[http://ufhealth.org/locations University of Florida Physician Practices]\n*[https://ufhealth.org/search/locations/rehabilitation UF Health Shands Rehab Centers]\n\n{{University of Florida}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital networks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Health care companies established in 1958]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Florida]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Florida]]\n[[Category:1958 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organizations based in Florida]]\n", "name_user": "SSyntaxin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a new image of the cancer and children's hospital", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Florida_Health"}
{"title_page": "Satellite Award for Best Miniseries or Television Film", "text_new": "The '''Satellite Award for Best Miniseries or TV Film''' is one of the annual [[Satellite Awards]] given by the [[International Press Academy]]. The IFA separated these two categories from 1999 to 2010 and from 2014 to 2015 as [[Satellite Award for Best Miniseries]] and [[Satellite Award for Best Television Film]].<ref>[http://www.pressacademy.com/award_cat/current-nominees/ 2016 Satellite Winners], May 2017.</ref>\n\n== Winners and nominees ==\n\n=== 1990s ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"95%\" cellpadding=\"5\"\n|-\n! width=\"10%\"|Year  \n! width=\"15%\"|Winners and nominees  \n! width=\"50%\"|Director(s)\n! width=\"25%\"|Network\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Satellite Awards 1996|1996]] || style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | '''''[[Gulliver's Travels (miniseries)|Gulliver's Travels]]'''''|| style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" |[[Charles Sturridge]] || style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | [[NBC]]\n|-\n| ''[[If These Walls Could Talk]]'' || [[Nancy Savoca]] and [[Cher]] || [[HBO]]\n|-\n| ''[[Pride and Prejudice (1995 TV serial)|Pride and Prejudice]]'' || [[Simon Langton (television director)|Simon Langton]] || [[A&E Network]]\n|-\n| ''[[The Siege at Ruby Ridge]]'' || [[Roger Young (director)|Roger Young]] || [[CBS]]\n|-\n| ''[[The Summer of Ben Tyler]]'' || [[Arthur Allan Seidelman]] || CBS\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Satellite Awards 1997|1997]] || style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | '''''[[Don King: Only in America]]'''''|| style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" |[[John Herzfeld]] || style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | HBO\n|-\n| ''[[Breast Men]]'' || Lawrence O'Neil || HBO\n|-\n| ''[[George Wallace (film)|George Wallace]]'' || [[John Frankenheimer]] || [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]]\n|-\n| ''[[Miss Evers' Boys]]'' || [[Joseph Sargent]] || HBO\n|-\n| ''[[The Odyssey (miniseries)|The Odyssey]]'' || [[Andrei Konchalovsky]] || NBC\n|-\n| ''[[Weapons of Mass Distr